Replication of Study: Why Do Skilled Immigrants Struggle in the Labor Market? A Field Experiment with Thirteen Thousand Resumes

Junaid Ahmed

27 April, 2020

Abstract

A replication of a study done to analyze why immigrants struggle in the labor market.

1 Introduction

This study was originally completed by Philip Oreopoulos at the Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab. He attempted to answer, “Why Do Skilled Immigrants Struggle in the Labor Market? A Field Experiment with Thirteen Thousand Resumes” His findings noted a few countries of origin that were discriminated against, but no other variables correlated.

The study only contains tables with correlations and various mathematical analyses. I will focus on recreating the linear model.

https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/WXMJCN

1.1 The Story Behind the Data

“Thousands of randomly manipulated resumes were sent in response to online job postings in Toronto to investigate why immigrants, allowed in based on skill, struggle in the labor market. The study finds substantial discrimination across a variety of occupations towards applicants with foreign experience or those with Indian, Pakistani, Chinese, and Greek names compared with English names. Listing language fluency, multinational firm experience, education from highly selective schools, or active extracurricular activities had no diminishing effect. Recruiters justify this behavior based on language skill concerns but fail to fully account for offsetting features when listed.”

1.2 Why it was gathered

The data was generated in order to examine whether discrimination was a viable explanation for difficulties with immigrant job search

1.3 Personal Interest in the Data

I would like to work with within the fields of immigration, education, poverty and policy, so this was interesting to me. This data was from a poverty lab, and I have applied to a few poverty labs for summer work experience

3 Initial Look at the Data

head(df)

The Variables that we have are:

  • frimid: job-posting identification number

  • occupation_type: job and resume occupation category

  • name_ethnicity: name ethnicity

  • additional_credential: indicator for additional credential added to all 4 resume types sent to employer because posting required it

  • name: name

  • language_skills: fluency in french and, for ethnic names, corresponding foreign language

  • accreditation: indicator for noting degree is accredited by the Canadian International Skills Certification Board

  • reference: indicator for canadian references listed

  • legal: indicator for permanent residency status

  • city: toronto, montreal, or vancouver

  • ma: indicator for resume listing masters degree

  • female: indicator for female name

  • ba_quality: indicator for whether bachelors’ degree from top ranked school

  • exp_highquality: indicator for whether experience from very large firm

  • callback: indicator that resume received callback

  • interview: indicator that interview specifically mentioned in callback

  • second_callback: indicator that resume received two callbacks

  • type:

    • Type 0: an applicant with an English sounding name, Canadian undergraduate education, and Canadian experience

    • Type 1: a foreign sounding name (Chinese, Indian, Pakistani, or Greek), but still listed Canadian undergraduate education and Canadian experience

    • Type 2: a foreign sounding name (Chinese, Indian, or Pakistani), corresponding foreign undergraduate degree, and Canadian experience

    • Type 3: a foreign sounding name, foreign education, and some foreign experience

    • Type 4: a foreign sounding name, foreign education, and all foreign experience

  • extracurricular_skills: indicator for whether (active) extracurricular skills listed

  • skillspeaking: ONET skill-speaking skills

  • skillsocialper: ONET skill social and personal skills

  • skillwriting: ONET skill writing skills

  • fall_data: indicator for 3 resume collection periods (see text)

  • same_exp: indicator for same firms listed across 4 resumes sent to same job

  data %>%
  group_by(type) %>%
  summarize(sum(fall_data)) %>%

  cbind(name = "Total", .)

#Summarizes results by resume frequency
data <-   
  data %>% 
  group_by(type, name, ethnicity, female) %>% 
  summarise(sum(fall_data)) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = type, values_from = `sum(fall_data)`) %>%
  arrange(ethnicity, female) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(-c(ethnicity, female)) %>%
  add_row(colSums)

5 Empirical Question and Methodology

5.1 Question

I would like to see whether there are other factors that may mitigate resume discrimination. For example, can we showcase graduate education or high-ranking bachelor degrees to quell concerns of competency among foreign individuals?

5.2 Equation

I will test bachelor’s education ranking, work experience, and whether or not the person has a Master’s degree. Our goal is to look for factors that curb potential discrimination.

In our econometric model, our independent variable will be the characteristics available to us such as education level, and our dependent variable will be the rate of job callbacks.

The regression equation given by the study is: \(y_{ijt} = \delta_0 + \delta_1Resume\_Type_{ijt} + \delta_2\textbf{X}_{ijt} + \delta_3[Resume\_Type_{ijt} \times \textbf{X}_{ijt}] + v_t + e_{ijt}\)

Explanation:

“Where \(y_{ijt}\) is an indicator variable for whether resume \(i\) sent to job posing \(j\) in period \(t\) generated a call back, \(Resume\_Type_{ijt}\) is an indicator variable for resume type, with the indicator for Type 0 being omitted. \(\textbf{X}_{ijt}\) is a vector of other resume characteristics. Equation (1) allows for interactions between resume type and other characteristics. This allows me to estimate, for example, whether callback differences between resumes with English and Chinese sounding names become smaller, when additional language skills or educational credentials are listed. Standard errors are corrected for possible heteroskedasticity by job.”

However, in this instance I will work on a simplified version of the model because including too many will quickly become complex.

Let us examine three models using different indicator variables.

First, one that tests whether the applicant’s bachelor’s degree is prestigious (top 200 world ranking university): \(callback = \beta_0 + \beta_1Resume\_Type + \beta_2prestige + \epsilon\)

Next, we test whether the applicant’s work experience is prestigious (multinational firm): \(callback = \beta_0 + \beta_1Resume\_Type + \beta_2workexp + \epsilon\)

Last, we test whether the person is fluent in other languages, including French: \(callback = \beta_0 + \beta_1Resume\_Type + \beta_2language + \epsilon\)

#Note: will not convert type to factor in order to prevent converison error with interaction term and because foreign characteristics increase as numbers increase
m1 <- lm(callback ~ type + ba_quality + type*ba_quality, data = df)
m2 <- lm(callback ~ type + exp_highquality + type*exp_highquality, data = df)
m3 <- lm(callback ~ type + language_skills + type*language_skills, data = df)

Before continuing further, we must check our assumptions needed for this linear model to be valid:

5.3 Gauss-Markov Assumptions needed to carry out SLR

We know that we have achieved all of these assumptions because the data was generated artificially for this study and the resumes were sent out to random companies within different cities in Canada. However, I will prove a few of these assumptions during our statistical analysis using various tests, such as t-testing. If there are abnormal results, such as a very high result, I will use more advanced methods such as testing multicolinearity with Variance Inflation Factor (VIF)

Simple linear regression relies on the following five assumptions (src: wooldridge p.65):

5.3.1 Equation is linear in parameters

\[y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i + \epsilon_i\]

5.3.2 Random Sampling of n observations

\[(x_i, y_i): i = 1, 2, ... n\]

5.3.3 Sample variation in explanatory variables

\(x_i\)’s are not all the same value \[x \neq (x_1 = x_2 = x_3 = ... = x_n)\]

5.3.4 Zero conditional mean

The error u has an expected value of 0, given any variables of the explanatory variable

\[E(u|x)=0\]

5.3.5 Homoskedasticity

The error has the same variance given any value of the explanatory variable \[Var(u|x) = \sigma^2\]

df %>%

From the table, I would be careful about the results because the data for callback, exp_highquality, and language_skills lean closer towards FALSE = 0 than TRUE = 1. ba_quality seems more balanced because it is 0.54, close to half.

However, I will once again be very skeptical of these preliminary visual results because most of the data heavily skews towards FALSE = 0. I will verify these exploratory results by running a regression and printing more statistically robust findings to a table.

According to the regression, BA prestige, experience prestige, and multilingualism do not have significant effects, although multilingualism has a small effect which is significant at the 10% level. In addition, my hypothesis that foreign backgrounds harm callbacks held true at the 1% level. To make these stronger, I will perform t-tests at the individual level.

5.5.2 Interpretation of \(R^2\) values

\(R^2\) gives us an approximation of how well the variables in the model explain the variance of the independent variable, callback. None of the models did particularly well because both the \(R^2\) and the adjusted \(R^2\) values were explained less than 1% of the variance in callback.

5.5.4 Hypothesis Testing

There is no reason for us to test heteroskedasticity, but we will check the significance of these results. If we were to suspect heteroskedasticity, I would use the Breush-Pagan test using the library lmtest.

5.5.4.2 F-testing using ANOVA

The F-test will measure whether there is a joint significance among the indicator variables.

restricted.model <- lm(callback ~ type, data = df)

Model 1: Bachelor Prestige

format(anova(restricted.model, m1), digits = 3)

We fail to reject the null hypothesis \(H0: \beta_{BA\_quality} = 0\)

Model 2: Work Experience Prestige

format(anova(restricted.model, m2), digits = 3)

We fail to reject the null hypothesis \(H0: \beta_{workexp\_quality} = 0\)

Model 3: Multilingual Ability

format(anova(restricted.model, m3), digits = 3)

Because p < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis \(H0: \beta_{multilingual} = 0\) and accept the alternative that \(H0: \beta_{multilingual} \neq 0\).

6 Conclusion

6.1 Answer to research question

There is significant discrimination based on the person’s level of separation from the home country. Foreign names, foreign work experience, and foreign educational institutions all contribute to receiving fewer callbacks.

We cannot say that bachelor’s degree prestige or experience prestige has an effect on curbing this discrimination. However, it seems as though multilingual abilities matter slightly. According to the author of the original study, Philip Oreopoulos, most employers were concerned about an applicant’s ability to speak English. They feared strong acents and not being understood by customers or coworkers. Names suggest fluency problems, work eligibility, long vacations to visit family/friends, and additional time off for cultural holidays (Oreopoulos 2011, p. 166).

From this short replication of the study, we have confirmed that multilingual ability may prevent some discrimination in the hiring market to help assuage some of these employers’ fears.

6.2 Literature Review

This is supported by Crandall and Eshleman (2003) who analyzed unintentional implicit discrimination and found that employers make assumptions based on people’s names. They assume immigration status and poor language skills.

Another study by Dan-Olof Rooth (2010) finds discrimination from Arab-Muslim names.

There are also similar results found by Bertrand, Chugh, and Mullainathan (2005). However, they see name-based discrimination between African-American names.

Lastly, Heblich et al. (2015) have found that accents do make a difference and there is a large concern around them. They say that they demonstrate that out-group accents lead to both social discrimination and economic decisions. This discrimination is based on social ratings of linguistic distance and the in-group/out-group perceptions.

6.3 Policy Implications

One immediate recommendation that is supported by Oreopoulos (2011) is that we should mask names to prevent discrimination. He also says that Goldin and Rouse (2000) document blind audition procedures fostering impartiality in hiring procedures.

6.4 Suggestions to improve model or experiment

This study was done well. However, I would recommend having a more even proportion of indicator variables. ba_quality was the only variable that was represented near 50%. However, I understand that this is difficult because of the sheer number of variables.
